Executive profile: Sally Grimes, Hillshire Brands - tribunedigital-chicagotribune




 



Executive profile: Sally Grimes of Hillshire BrandsChief innovation officer combines expertise in food and marketingMay 25, 2014|By Jessica Wohl, Tribune reporterHillshire Brands’ Sally Grimes walks through Standard Market, which she helped persuade to carry the company’s Aidells sausage. (Zbigniew Bzdak, Chicago Tribune)A weekend visit to Costco often results in buying more than one planned. For Sally Grimes, putting an extra item into an oversized shopping cart led to Hillshire Brands Co. buying another company.As the chief innovation officer of Chicago-based Hillshire Brands, Grimes is constantly looking for unusual products and flavors — and determining if they are things Hillshire should try to develop or acquire.While at Costco, a display of Golden Island jerky caught her eye. She bought a bag, tasted it and took it to the office, where she shared it with colleagues, including Hillshire CEO Sean Connolly.Flavorful and tender, it was a hit and sparked Grimes' interest in learning more about the product."I said, 'Can I give them a call?'" Grimes recalled. She got the company's phone number from its website and left a message for its president, Anna Kan.They began talking and a relationship blossomed. In September 2013, Hillshire bought Golden Island.The idea of Hillshire swooping in to buy a company that makes a high-end product would have seemed ridiculous a few years ago for a company better known for budget-friendly staples like sausage biscuits and hot dogs. But these days, Hillshire is on an acquisition tear as it looks for ways to stand out in the U.S. packaged-food industry. It announced plans this month to buy Pinnacle Foods, the maker of Birds Eye frozen vegetables, Duncan Hines cake mix and Vlasic pickles, for about $4.3 billion.Along with pantry staples, Hillshire also is adding artisanal, upscale products to its lineup and aiming to add an innovative spark to familiar lines such as Jimmy Dean sausage, Ball Park franks and Hillshire Farm deli meat.Grimes, 43, is the person in charge of both efforts. Her role, which has expanded in the past year with the additional title of president of the gourmet food group, harnesses some 17 years in the food and consumer marketing worlds at Kraft and Newell Rubbermaid."If we use our imagination, the possibilities are endless," Grimes said.When Hillshire started out on its own in 2012 after decades under the Sara Lee umbrella, CEO Sean Connolly knew the company needed to focus on innovation to stand out in an increasingly crowded and slow-growing U.S. grocery market. Only 9 percent of its sales came from products introduced in the prior three years, while industry leaders have levels closer to the midteens. Hillshire set a goal of getting to 13 to 15 percent by fiscal 2015.Hillshire now has a roster of newer products in its lineup, such as Jimmy Dean Delights Flatbread sandwiches and Park's Finest by Ball Park hot dogs. Next month it will launch 16 Jimmy Dean items that push the brand beyond breakfast. Those include frozen ham and cheddar cheese sandwiches on pretzel buns and smoked bacon macaroni and cheese.Under Grimes, the innovation department has shaved about 10 weeks off the company's product creation process, bringing the average down to 35 weeks. The flatbreads came out in about one-third of that time, a company record.Hillshire's percentage of sales from new products hit 11 percent last year and is now closer to 12 percent.When Hillshire started on its own, it decided to appoint an executive in charge of innovation, a title that does not exist at major U.S. food companies."In a lot of companies, innovation is a mature process and where it is being executed it's not a necessary role," said Connolly. "We were a new company, we needed to make things happen quickly. I needed to send a clear message to the entire enterprise that innovation was an imperative at Hillshire."The question of who should take that job was answered when Connolly heard about Grimes through Andy Callahan, who had worked with her years before at Kraft Foods and is now president of Hillshire's retail business. Connolly called Grimes in June 2012, when she was working at Newell Rubbermaid, to talk about whether she would be interested in joining his company."When I met Sally it was clear to me that she just has a really good handle on our consumer base and what they're passionate about, what they struggle with and she's very creative" in acting on what the consumer needs, Connolly said.And Grimes, who had helped transform the image of Sharpie markers from a basic desk supply to a cool tool for creative expression, felt it was the right time for a change. She started at Hillshire that July."I was so inspired by his vision" to make Hillshire into the most innovative food company in the United States, she said. Plus, "I always thought I would find my way back into food."Immigrant parentsGrimes grew up in Bourbonnais, about an hour south of Chicago, raised by parents who emigrated from India in the 1960s to pursue their education. Her first name is Shobana, an Indian name that translates to "bright." Her middle name, Sally, was picked to honor her mother's first American friend after she arrived in the U.S.Her mother was a dietitian focused on the science of food.1 | 2 | 3 |  Next


