Q&A
Sally Grimes of Hillshire Brands aims to speed new products to market



                  Sally Grimes (Hillshire Brands photo)
                





              By Kate MacArthur, Special to Blue Sky
              
Oct. 29, 2013, 6:05 a.m.


Sally Grimes has a knack for reimagining products you think you already know. At Kraft Foods Inc., she made macaroni and cheese microwaveable. At Newell Rubbermaid Inc., she elevated the Sharpie pen to a wand of artistic expression. Now, as president of Hillshire Brands Gourmet Food Group and chief innovation officer of Hillshire Brands Co., Grimes is working to do the same for meat. Already, she has overseen the launch of a new product called Jimmy Dean Flatbread breakfast sandwiches in a company-record 12 weeks -- the time from initial concept to first shipment. She told us more about her approach to innovation. 
Q. Hillshire has said it wants to be the most innovative company in the meat business. What will that mean?
A. Historically, we have averaged about 45 weeks of getting an innovation into the marketplace. We set out a goal of hitting 35 weeks. Secondly, historically we’ve been able to look ahead and understand about a year’s worth of innovation. We set a goal of ensuring we had a three-year, sustainable pipeline at all times.
Lastly, and I would say most importantly, historically, we have averaged about 9 percent of our revenue from innovation, and we set a goal to deliver 13 [percent] to 15 percent of revenue from innovation by fiscal year 2015. And that third metric is really what I focus on.
Q. How will you make that happen?
A. We homed in on two key focus areas. First was getting deeper insights. In some cases in the past, we didn't go deep enough on understanding the consumer and, in turn, delivering a meaningful point of difference.
The second is all about stronger execution. One of the things that we have instituted is rapid prototyping. In the case of Jimmy Dean Flatbreads, we were able to leverage our innovation center where we have the ability to rapidly prototype products and get them in front of consumers quickly, get the feedback, make changes immediately, and get in front of consumers again. That’s one aspect of being more flexible and more nimble with this new process.
Q. How do you divide your efforts between incremental versus radical innovation?
A. We have two key pillars to this growth strategy. One is sustaining innovation. This means packaging innovation, quality improvement, sustaining the growth of our core brands through new flavors and forms. We’ve got some amazing, iconic bands that haven't been nurtured that much, so that is critically important right now because we need the foundation from which to grow.
The second part is about extending the reach of our brands and our business beyond the products and categories in which we serve today. It’s saying Jimmy Dean is not just about breakfast. Jimmy Dean is not just about sausage. Jimmy Dean is about hearty comfort food. So how can we take that amazing iconic trademark into new categories, new forms.
Q. How does innovation differ among the companies where you've worked?
A. To put it into simple terms, you ask three main questions: Will they want it, meaning the consumer; can we make it and can we make money at it? At a very basic level, I have followed that both at Kraft and Newell Rubbermaid.
What is different about Hillshire is a commitment from the top. When you put that word [innovation] in your vision statement, it means that innovation isn't just something that you’ll do. It means that innovation is something that defines you. 
Q-and-A’s are edited for clarity and length.














